Class EntityAccess

  • java.lang.Object
    • proj.w41k4z.orm.spec.EntityAccess
  • public abstract class EntityAccess
extends Object
    EntityAccess is an abstract class used to access entity information through its useful static methods.

      • getAllEntityFields

        public static EntityField[] getAllEntityFields​(Class<?> entityClass,
                                               Class<?> sourceEntity)
        Get all the entity column fields with their source entity, with inherited fields. This exclude fields with a relationship annotation (Only those annotated with @Column are taken).
        Parameters:
        entityClass - the entity class
        sourceEntity - the entity class associated to the field concerned. If null, the entityClass will be used instead
        Returns:
        the entity column fields

      • getEntityFields

        public static EntityField[] getEntityFields​(Class<?> entityClass)
        Get the entity column fields. The difference with the getAllEntityFields(Class, Class) is that it may exclude some inherited column fields according to the inheritance type occuring. And also, this include fields with relationship annotation. To be simple, these are the fields that will be used when inserting or updating an entity.
        Parameters:
        entityClass - the entity class
        Returns:
        the entity column fields

      • getRelatedEntityChildren

        public static EntityChild[] getRelatedEntityChildren​(Class<?> entityClass)
        Get all related children of the given entity class (Inheritance supported). Children are those fields annotated with a relationship annotation such as @OneToOne, @OneToMany, @ManyToMany.
        Parameters:
        entityClass - the entity class
        Returns:
        the related children

      • getRelatedEntityClasses

        public static Class<?>[] getRelatedEntityClasses​(Class<?> entityClass)
        Get all the tables associated to the entity class. This method is meant to return wether an array of one or two elements. Because it mainly concerns the JOINED_TABLE inheritance type. The first element of the array is the main/source table, and the rest is its dependencies (parent table to join...)
        Parameters:
        entityClass - the entity class
        Returns:
        the entity classes related to the given entity class
